Notes:

Customer has unique code at most granular level (Model, color, size etc.)

Customer does not have activeness attribute. Some assumptions must be implemented to retrieve this information.

Even before product is produced, some transactions may occur including these items, so these should be included in tables. (Barcode data)

Opening date is not available. Workaround: First inventory action in that store.

We need to distinguish active/passive stores. (Customer has this classification. Two categories: LFL stores and new stores)

Store renovation (closing store for a very limited period): Full shutdown is very rare case. An indication should be sent. It can also be managed manually with 'Client Excellence Team'.

Passive stores: Customer keeps the information of closed stores. Technically, it still remains without any sales and inventory.

eps the information of closed stores. Technically, it still remains without any sales and inventory.

Store capacity is managed manually right now, but this information can be delivered to Invent team. For phase 1, we can ignore it and consider it for the next phases.

All stores can include all products right now. But these limitations can be set later on. (Dubai vs Saudi Arabia)

Price varies from country to country even for the same product.

Notes:

Goods in Transit table:

- There is no Departure Date field on M&S side. PGI Date (SAP) can be used instead of Departure Date.
- M&S does not have ‘Estimated Departure Date’ information. This information is not mandatory.

Purchase Order table:

- There is no ‘Departure Date’ field on M&S side. PGI Date (SAP) can be used instead of Departure Date.
- M&S side will check if Quantity cancelled information can be reached.

Transactional Sales table:

- We all must be sure that Transaction Id is unique. An existing field can be used or new field can be created by using combination of several existing fields.
- There are several sales type indicators like FP and RP. Sales Type field will be checked on M&S side.

Case pack Quantity table:

indicators like FP and RP. Sales Type field will be checked on M&S side.

Case pack Quantity table:

- First comment on M&S side: There is no limitation for sending products. It can be 3 XL, 1 Medium etc. Not even for socks. Further checks will be made on M&S side.

Order schedule and Product Destination Source Relation tables

- Requirement are described by Invent. M&S will check internally.

Product table:

- 1st level of hierarchy: Department

2nd level of hierarchy: Collection

Lead time table:

- On store level, lead times are always 1 day. However, if we include vendors, lead times are much higher and moreover M&S does not have this information.

Product Location Status table:

- Active/Inactive statuses can be provided.

Price table

formation.

Product Location Status table:

- Active/Inactive statuses can be provided.

Price table

- There two type of prices: Standard price and markdown price. They both have start and end date fields. End date of standard price is 31.12.9999. On the other hand, specific start and end date information is used on markdown side. It can also be a markdown for future period (Starting with 01.08.2021 etc.)

First price table

- Start and end date columns must be added in this table.

Notes:Season table:

- Can be captured from SAP by unique identifier. (Season code and season name exists in SAP. However, start and end date information does not exist in SAP)
- We can go on with quarters. There are four season (Winter, Fall, Spring, Summer) in system.
- Products can overlap at the same season. For example, winter products can still be sold at spring season. Spring products can still be sold at summer season season.

Markdown Warehouse table:

- There are just two warehouses (one small warehouse and the other big one in Dubai). Since they both have markdown products, we do not have to distinguish the markdown ones. This table will be same with warehouse table.

Markdown Items table:

- Available

- Clusters can be created manually later on. Dubai, KSA etc. Clusters will be created according to thier countries.

be created manually later on. Dubai, KSA etc. Clusters will be created according to thier countries.

- Hierarchy information here must be aligned with the ones at Product table.
- Store Agg Level information may solve the country differentiation problem.

Cost table:

- Cost date: The time the last change occurs. (Recent change date)

Promotion Information table:

- It is highly recommended to deliver this information. It will be discussed on M&S for possibilities to deliver it.

Ecom table:

- Originating Location Code: Not required / Only done through website
- M&S will investigate if there is any difference between marketplace and website

Ecom Sales table:

- Fulfilment types are available on M&S side.

Casepack Quantity table:

- Casepack quantity is applicable only for Home and Beauty products.

Next Step: M&S Data Engineering Team will work on requirements and ask questions to Invent team if necessary.

·         Currently M&S trades through the web site across MENA and Asia markets except Egypt.

·         The data flows from the UK. All they do in the region is to facilitate the customer journey. Everything is picked, packed, and dispatched from the UK.

·         With the transition, they’ll migrate the web site and platform to the AFG platforms. This includes merchandising, marketing, and warehouse operations (pick, pack, and dispatch). M&S also will have hybrid store module along with warehouse for the fulfillment.

·         There will be 4 fulfillment locations in Dubai for UAE. (3 flagship stores + warehouse) For the markets other than UAE, the orders will be picked from the local stores. If required, UAE warehouse will ship them out.

·         UK still might need pick up and ship to the region some products in the UK catalogue hat are not initially purchased by M&S Dubai. The data will come from the local markets. This is the added complexity in the model.

by M&S Dubai. The data will come from the local markets. This is the added complexity in the model.

·         Current omnichannel exercises such as home delivery, click & collect, in-store ordering will be maintained after the transition. Delivery to third party lockers will be added.

·         A sale from an endless aisle is going to be processed through the store if the store has inventory to fulfill the demand.

·         Required data currently not available for M&S Dubai. They will be automatically stored in the system after February going forward.

·         E-com sales is around 5% of total sales.

·         The team to discuss with UK for historical data requirements.

General

·         The business aims to reduce overall inventory.

·         Week cover is currently 22 weeks, the goal is 15 weeks. (Store Inventory? Overall Inventory (Store + DC)?

Inventory Planning for Warehouse

·         Option plan is done at the time buying.

·         M&S buys 4 times a year. No repeat orders in between. Might be rare opportunities to top up.

·         For core lines and key products, M&S buys 16 weeks of inventory (4 weeks for safety stock)

·         The planning is done for the seasons 9 months in advance. Currently M&S do the option planning for Summer 22 as of 1st of Sep 21.

Brand-new products / initial allocation

1. How the allocation starts? The reorder points (at product level) are set-up in SAP when the inventory arrives at the DC. The team checks the option fulfillment of the stores which the product is catalogued to (whether the stores can accommodate it and if the option fulfillment is lower 100% then they start allocating it).

tores can accommodate it and if the option fulfillment is lower 100% then they start allocating it).

1. Then they decide how many singles each store should receive considering a) cost b) sale rate c) lead time. They break it down to size level based on the buying ratio. The replenishment job is run overnight, and the shipments are made. This is a complete manual process.

1. M&S does the initial allocation at two phases for some seasons. For Autumn, phase 1 at the beginning of September, phase 2 at the beginning of October. However, this depends on the season as well. M&S might need to perform initial allocation at different points of the season for some departments.

Core products / regular replenishment

1. The replenishment is run based on one-to-one sale.

1. The team manually increases / decreases reorder points before special event / promotion starts (Eid, Ramadan etc.) based on historical activities.

r points before special event / promotion starts (Eid, Ramadan etc.) based on historical activities.

1. The stores are prioritized for each business unit / category in case of restricted inventory at the warehouse. (Prioritization mainly made based on historical run rate but amount of available inventory might be a factor)

1. The current method calculates reorder points based on weekly average sales. The lead times vary from 1 day to 30. Example given indicated that the lead time was 3 weeks for Qatar and the reorder point is set as 40 whereas weekly average sales is 10 units.

1. The order frequency stays the same 90% of the time. UAE stores orders every day. The other markets have a certain schedule.

Store – to – Store transfer

1. The transfer decisions are made manually from lower performing store to the better.

1. No store-to-store transfer performed when there is sufficient inventory at the warehouse.

etter.

1. No store-to-store transfer performed when there is sufficient inventory at the warehouse.

1. Example: End of sales period stock consolidation – M&S might want to consolidate all of the sale lines at a high foot traffic store.

1. Store lead times should be taken into consideration when prioritizing the stores

## Module Details

·         M&S makes transfer decisions every other week (frequency = approximately 15 days)

·         The compliance rate to the suggested transfer decisions is around 95%

·         M&S measures overall sell through improvement to calculate the effectiveness of the transfer decisions

·         Invent measures sales return instead, both will be reported

·         M&S aims to cover approximately 3-4 weeks of sales when making the transfer decisions

·         Forecasts are calculated based on rate of sales, stockouts are also considered.

·         There are not “blocked” products in the transfer process (products that are not allowed to move between stores), however the product – store definitions (scope table) must be taken into consideration as one product should not be sent out to a store where it is not defined by data

·         Packaging might take 2-3 days at the origin store

Consolidation transfers follow the following path: store – warehouse – store. The transportation might take 1-2 days if it is only store-to-store.

2021-09-16 Workshop Meeting NotesGeneral

●        The meeting focused on the flow of markdown process and the important points that need attention

Points to consider for the specific countries

●        Markdown list for 3 phases is submitted together 3 weeks in advance for Oman & Bahrain

●        Prices mentioned in the submitted list should be strictly followed for Oman & Bahrain and can not be changed after submitting

●        Markdown list is submitted 1 week in advance for UAE

●        Phasing calendar compliance should be considered for Oman & Bahrain

Markdown Process

UAE

●        Phasing calendar compliance should be considered for Oman & Bahrain

Markdown Process

1. Discounts start on Wednesdays, but prices are entered into the system on Monday
2. Stocks are consolidated in stores, there is no discounted stock in the warehouses at the beginning of the clearance period
3. Sales, Stock, Sell Through are tracked at country, option and store level
4. Markdown KPIs are calculated on the stock value
5. Age is calculated from the day the product first appears in the warehouse
6. Aged lines start with 50% discount
7. The price change days of countries and how long each phase will last can vary from country to country
8. Markdown intervals given in the phasing calendar are used as minimum and maximum discount boundaries.
9. Intervals in the phasing calendar do not enforce a number of discount changes per item throughout the sales period. Items can change discounts more than 3,4 times during the sales period.

throughout the sales period. Items can change discounts more than 3,4 times during the sales period.

10)   New products can enter the discount from phase 2 or phase 3

11)   Calculations like Sell Through, Markdown are tracked in 3 groups which are S (first time sale in clearance), CY (clear as you go) and E (was on sale in previous clearance)

12)   Target Sell Through is updated at the end of each sale phase

13)   T35, T36, T47 Category price decisions are made on size level, for other categories price decisions are made on color level.

Calculations

●        Markdown : (FP-RP) * Sell Through

Sell Through : SalesRevenue / StockValue (FullPriceValue)

Markdown : (FP-RP) * Sell Through

Sell Through : SalesRevenue / StockValue (FullPriceValue)

·         And the order quantities are calculated considering store on hand inventory, store in-transit inventory and open orders.

·         The team regularly reviews the screen to see if there are new products to be allocated. They show zero BTF on the screen.

Reports are delivered to the client in two way, via UI and Tableau. UI reports are exported to the afg-file-manager container in Azure Blob. Tableau reports are written under invent-afg-datastore/reporting directory and connected with Tableau server.

Functional UI reports include actions that directly affect the order generation process. Based on criterias both defined by and project teams, targets are created and written to invent-afg-datastore/internal-data/target_modifier_internal/fix_target without any usage of rocket module. This enables us to create orders for pairs that cannot be detected by scope generation for some reason.

Optimizasyon modeline minimum sevkiyat limiti kısıtı eklendi. `enable_min_shipment_capacity` parametresi üzerinden kısıt aktive edilebilir. Model, shipment capacity verisinde bulunan her kapasite grubu için tanımlanmış minimum adetlerde sipariş oluşturmayı hedefler. Eğer bu minimum adette sipariş çıkmıyorsa kapasite grubuna hiç sipariş oluşmaz.

Minimum sevkiyat limiti kısıtı kullanıldığı taktirde ihtiyacın (rounded need) üzerinde sipariş çıkabilmesi için total cost datasındaki ürün-mağaza ikililerinin maksimum adetlerinin artırılması gerekmekte. Bu amaçla AFG için linkteki upperbound_quantity extension u kullanılabilir: [https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/pipeline/alfuttaim/-/blob/main/rocks_extension/rocket/upperbound_quantity.py](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/pipeline/alfuttaim/-/blob/main/rocks_extension/rocket/upperbound_quantity.py)

Hesaplama mantığı şu şekilde:

metadata.title: Allocation - Minimum Shipment Quantity Constraint Use

content:
/alfuttaim/-/blob/main/rocks_extension/rocket/upperbound_quantity.py)

Hesaplama mantığı şu şekilde:

Kapasite limiti capacity_extension_ratio ile genişletilir (extended capacity). Toplam karşılanabilir ihtiyaç ve ihtiyacın kapasitenin ne kadar altında kaldığı (extended need) hesaplanır. Artan depo stok (excess supply) çıkarılır.

Kapasite artış miktarı (extended need) depo stoklu ürün mağaza ikililerine target oranlarında dağıtılır (extended target). İhtiyaç ve target oranında dağıtılmış kapasite artışları toplanır (extended pair needs). Depo stoğuyla caplenerek upperbound_temp değerleri hesaplanır.

Cover period max demand, inventory, upperbound_temp ve rounded_need in maksimumu upperbound quantity olarak seçilir.

Configden yönetilebilecek 2 parametre var:

metadata.title: Allocation - Minimum Shipment Quantity Constraint Use

content:
ed_need in maksimumu upperbound quantity olarak seçilir.

Configden yönetilebilecek 2 parametre var:

- default_capacity_extension_ratio: (default = 1.2) --> Tanımlanan kapasite değerini expand etmek için kullanılır. Quantity lerin kapasitenin üzerinde expand edilmesi, sistemin verebileceği kararlar konusunda esneklik sağlar.Örneğin kapasite 1000, need 500. Quantity artışı: (1000*1.2) - 500 = 700 adet
- replace_order_up_to_level: (default = 0.1) --> Quantity expand edilirken ikililerin targetlarına oranla expand edilir. Target ı 0 olan ürünler için de quantityler oluşsun (karar çıkabilsin) isteniyorsa bu değer üzerinden oranı yönetilebilir.

Bu modul pipeline da casepack rounder dan sonra, lost sales ve excess inventory cost tan önce konumlanmalı.

metadata.title: Allocation - Minimum Shipment Quantity Constraint Use

content:
l pipeline da casepack rounder dan sonra, lost sales ve excess inventory cost tan önce konumlanmalı.

Canlıya almak için bu MR da silinen kısımlar (total_cost ile ilgili kısımlar hariç) repoya eklenmeli: [https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/pipeline/alfuttaim/-/merge_requests/1571/diffs](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/pipeline/alfuttaim/-/merge_requests/1571/diffs). Data context e forecast_sum, volatility, inventory, supply , order_up_to_level ve capacity_pairs dataları eklenmeli.

Default config de excess inventory cost ve lost sales cost modüllerinin kullandığı upper_bound quantity verisi rounded_need den okunmakta. Total cost datasındaki ikililerin maksimum adetlerini artırmak için upperbound modül çıktısı kullanılmalı.

Upperbound_quantity nin default schemasında değişiklik yapılırsa rocket/controls/config.yaml ve rocket/reporting/config.yaml da upperbound_quantity nin scheması güncellenmeli.

metadata.title: Allocation - Minimum Shipment Quantity Constraint Use

content:
trols/config.yaml ve rocket/reporting/config.yaml da upperbound_quantity nin scheması güncellenmeli.

Excess inventory cost un artış hızı lost sales cost tan daha yavaş. Bu da minimum sevkiyat kısıtı açıkken ihtiyacın çok üzerinde bir kapasite tanımlandığında dahi sipariş adetlerinin minimum kapasiteye tamamlanmasına sebep oluyor. (0 stok bırakmanın toplam maliyeti >Yüksek stok oluşturmanın toplam maliyeti)

*Örnek ürün-mağaza ikilisi*

İhtiyacın üzerinde kalan adetler için total cost değerinin artırılmasını sağlayan bir extention ekledik. Total cost u artırmaya gittik çünkü allocation ürünlerinin belirli bir süre sonra yeni sezonda zararına satılacağını öngörüyoruz. Bu extension canlıya alındığında sipariş oluşturmayı stoksuz bırakmaya tercih etme oranı düşecektir. Böylelikle optimizasyon, ihtiyacın daha yüksek olduğu durumlarda siparişleri minimum sevkiyat kapasitesine tamamlar. Çok düşük ihtiyaç durumunda siparişleri 0 a çekmeyi tercih edecektir. X günlük forecast toplamı ve rounded_need in maksimumu alınır. Bu maksimum değerin üzerindeki adetlerin costlarında total cost, quantity farkı * cogs * salvage ratio değeri eklenerek artırılır.

`for total_cost quantities > max(X days forecast sum - inventory , optimal point)`

`total_cost = total_cost + (quantity - max(X days forecast sum - inventory , optimal point)) * cogs * salvage_ratio`

Configden yönetilebilecek 3 parametre var:

- salvage_ratio:  (default = 1.0) Total cost a ekleme yaparken ürünün cogs * salvage ratio su ekleniyor. Bu oran cost değerini artırmak/azaltmak için değiştirilebilir.

content: This page describes the daily process flow of Alfuttaim Project, starting from the data transfer process start to the end of rocket-early run.

Hello! This is the welcome page for Alfuttaim (a.k.a AFG) Project! Under this Handbook section, you will see useful information and details on who we are as the project team and how we do things in the project. Please let us know if you have any comments to improve!

This page is to show how we do things!
## Jira task management

To ease our time management, we have a continuous task list. Please log your work to these if the definition of your task fall under one of these & feel free to add new continuous tasks when needed.

### AFG-Replenishment Project Continuous Tasks List

Jira Adjustments:

Client meeting:

Internal meeting:

KPI Check:

Daily process fails:

New line allocation:

Scope Adjustments:

Fail log diary updates:

Report debug:   (Please do create a new task for each individual report bug related to this one as a subtask)

Service customer general:

Service internal general:

Sale line allocation:   (Use when there is a request for manual order creation for sale line products)

New store allocation:   (Use when there is a new store opening which requires manual order creation)

Not allocated lines allocation:   (Use when the client asks about the missing lines/manually created orders to be added into our system)

se when the client asks about the missing lines/manually created orders to be added into our system)

IA run result check:   (Use when there is a need for daily initial allocation result check)

Hopefully these will reduce in number via automatization of manual processes

What to do when a new store opens?

1. It should be added to the store.csv and store_table.csv files that we receive in the daily data transfer.
2. It should be added to the invent-afg-datastore/internal-data/extracted_lead_time.csv to include in the order schedule. We can ask client side for the reference stores.
3. It should be added to the invent-afg-datastore/internal-data/ia_target_cap_values.csv to create proper amounts of IA orders. We can ask client side for the reference stores.

1. internal-data altındaki extracted lead time csv dosyasına bu BU için ilgili tüm mağazalara lead time tanımlanmasını sağlamak gerek, müşteriyle dosyayı paylaşıp eklemeleri istenebilir.
2. Yeni gelen BU product.csv datasında bulunmalı
3. Eğer bu ürünler daha önceden başka bir BU ile geliyorduysa zaten satış ve stok kayıtları olduğundan scope’a girebilir ama yepyeni ürünlerse ve müşteri bunlar için target paylaştıysa bu targetların tanımlanması ve bu pairlerin scope_addition.csv dosyasına eklenmesi gerekir.
4. IA kapsamında sonuç çıkması isteniyorsa target cap values csv dosyasına bu BUlar eklenmeli.
5. Reporting tasklarınında BU filtreleniyor olabilir, bunlara bakılıp ekleme yapılmalı.
6. Nerelere ekleme yapılacağını belirlemenin en temiz yolu alfuttaim reposunda JAEGER veya KIDSWEAR gibi bir BU ismini aratmak ve kontrol etmektir. Son adımda bu yapılırsa yeni BU için sonuç çıktığına ve raporlarda yer aldığına emin olunabilir.

Frequently olmasa da zaman zaman sorulabilecek soruların cevaplarını buraya ekliyorum:

1. Early Push nasıl açılır, genel logic'i nedir?

- Early Push/Look Ahead parametresinin nasıl çalıştığının genel açıklaması şuradaki Rocket dokümantasyonunda anlatılıyor.
- AFG'de parametrenin nasıl açıldığı/test edildiği şu taskta anlaılıyor:
- Dikkat: Pandas geçişi yapıldıktan sonra configlerin yapısı değişecektir, o durumda bu parametrenin nasıl açılacağı ile ilgili Rocket ekibine danışılabilir.

1. Dag hata aldığında yeni rocket dag'i tetiklemeAFG'de target hesaplama adımları yalnızca Early Runlarda çalışıyor. Gece çalışan Runlarda target hesaplanmıyor. Early run hata alırsa ve vaktinde düzeltilmezse gece çalışan runlar ya hata alır ya da bir önceki günün targetları ile çalışır. Early runda problemin düzeltilemediği ve gece çalışan runın hata aldığı durumda hata kaynağı bulunup çözüldüğünde güncel targetlar hesaplanarak yeni bir run çalıştırmak istenebilir.

ata kaynağı bulunup çözüldüğünde güncel targetlar hesaplanarak yeni bir run çalıştırmak istenebilir.

Bu durumda rocket_daily daginde sağ üst köşede (aşağıda gösterilen yerden) run with configs seçeneği ile yeni bir run başlatılabilir.

Açılan pencerede run başlatmak için parametreler yine aşağıda gösterildiği şekilde verilir.

```
{"run_date": "2023-01-17",
"run_type": "early",
"product_type": ["store_rpl", "ia"],
"env_type": "prod",
"calculate_target": "true"}
```

Alınan test run olarak alınacaksa env_type='test' olarak verilmelidir, prod değil.

Target hesaplanması istenmiyorsa calculate_target=false olarak verilebilir, bu durumda en son hesaplanmış targetlar kullanılır.

Bu yeni runın sonuçları müşteriye gönderilmek istenirse daily dagde çalışan send_output kodu (aşağıdaki şekilde) Databricks notebookunda çalışıtırılarak sonuçların ilgili output bucketına yazılması sağlanır ve daily dagdeki send_output taskı success olarak işaretlenir.

i output bucketına yazılması sağlanır ve daily dagdeki send_output taskı success olarak işaretlenir.

```
output_prefix = "2023-09-01T012010.508Z"
run_id = "2023-09-01-store_rpl-ia-38dd3c3b"
run_date = "2023-09-01"

sc.addFile("dbfs:/FileStore/version-upgrade/src/rocks_extension", recursive=True)
from rocks_extension.opal.send_output import AlfuttaimGroupOutput

instance = AlfuttaimGroupOutput(
  config_section="allocation_order",
  customer_config_path="/dbfs/FileStore/src/scripts/opal/config.yaml",
  output_prefix=output_prefix,
  run_id=run_id,
  run_date=run_date
)

instance.run()
```

Bu yapıldıktan sonra sonuçların FTP'ye yazıldığı task başarılı bir şekilde tamamlanmalıdır. Bu yöntem izlenirse client_reporting dagi run_id'yi daily dag'den alacağı için doğru şekilde çalışamaz ve hata alır. Bu nedenle client_reporting dagindeki tasklar manuel olarak notebooktan çalıştırılmalıdır veya rocket_daily gibi config parametreleri verilerek (yeni rocket run_id ile) run edilmelidir.

## Guiding thoughts

Starting a new project can be overwhelming, so here are some guiding thoughts to integrate smoothly and feel comfortable in your new project

ng, so here are some guiding thoughts to integrate smoothly and feel comfortable in your new project

- Take time to learn. Don't get sucked into the minutia of decision-making or project involvement too early - there will be plenty of time for that later. In your handover process, focus on getting comfortable and learning how things work.
- Don't be afraid to ask. No one expects you to know how things at the project work right away. Take advantage of that and ask for help when you need it.
- Be Proactive: If you see areas that could be improved, suggest constructive changes. Fresh perspectives are often valuable for continuous improvements.
- Stay Organized: Make sure you follow the handover steps in a planned manner and complete all items.

## Flow

- The customer sends daily data to invent-liwa-input-dev container in Microsoft Azure Storage every night at 3.30 AM.
- Daily dag starts running at 3.15 AM - the client is  providing a manifest file. The daily dag will move on to other tasks as soon as there is the new input file directory with date and timestamp.
- All files are pushed at once so there is no partial upload of the files.
- We receive a total of 31 files in the daily flow. All of these are listed in the pre-ETL sheet. Azure location: inventliwashared/invent-liwa-input-dev/historypre_etl_codesNotebook for pre-etl checks
- Results are saved in the inventliwashared/invent-liwa-output-dev folder, from which the client retrieves the data. Outputs should be available no later than 6:15 AM TR time.
- If results are not delivered to the customer by 6:15 AM TR time, an email is sent both to the customer and to us. (rpl_results_fail_mail)

1. Check your mail box:  To access the logs page of a failed task, please use the provided Log link. This will directly take you to the logs page where you can find more information about the error. Please note that identifying the problem by looking at the logs may be difficult.In such cases, it is recommended to check the Databricks job run if the issue is not related to Databricks or airflow, or any other mechanical problem. By doing so, you can get a better understanding of the problem and find a suitable solution. If you already familiar with the error and you think there is no need to track, Mark success link leads you where you can mark the task as success in order to prevent all the other dags to be failed.

eads you where you can mark the task as success in order to prevent all the other dags to be failed.
2. Check cicd slack channel: To easily access the DAG  in case of Airflow errors, please check the CICD Slack channel. This is the most convenient way to find and resolve errors related to Airflow. By checking the CICD Slack channel, you can quickly identify the specific DAG where the error occurred and take necessary actions to resolve it.

3.   Find the failed task: If above two step does not give you an idea about the what may be the problem, go to the Airflow web interface and find the DAG that contains the failed task. Click on the DAG to view the DAG's graph view. Failed tasks will appear in red. Click on the failed task to see more information about the task's failure. Once you are here, you can click on See Databricks Job Runto directly see the logs of the task.

Check Task Logs

Once you have identified the failed task, check the task logs to determine the cause of the failure. You can find the task logs by clicking on the failed task in the DAG graph view and then clicking on the Logs tab. Look for any error messages or stack traces that may provide clues to the cause of the failure. As stated earlier this can only give you an idea about if the task is failed due to a mechanical problem. In order to identify the real problem click on See Databricks Job Run.

The job run logs contain valuable information that can help us pinpoint the cause of the failure. The red part of the log indicates the exact point where the problem arose, step by step. The white part shows everything that happened until you reach that point.

When someone ask you send full trace of the log, send them standard error file or directly the job run link.Fix the Issue

Once you have identified the cause of the failure, fix the issue. Depending on the issue, there are different ways to fix the task. Here are some common fixes:

- Fixing a coding error: If the task failed due to a coding error, fix the error and re-run the task.
- Increasing resources: If the task failed due to insufficient resources, such as memory or CPU, increase the resources and re-run the task.
- Adjusting parameters: If the task failed due to incorrect parameters, adjust the parameters and re-run the task.

rameters: If the task failed due to incorrect parameters, adjust the parameters and re-run the task.

> Info: Error Sources: Development: Errors resulting from development work, and the development needs to be revised by going back to the source. Customer Data Related: Errors that occur when there is a lack of data, incorrect data, or missing data from the customer. Communication with the customer should be established to resolve the issue. Airflow: Errors related to Airflow, such as triggering of interconnected tasks or connection problems. The source of the error should be resolved and the task may need to be re-run if necessary. Timeout: Errors that occur when the specified time for triggering or waiting for a task is exceeded. The source of the error should be identified, and the task may need to be re-run.Delta Cache: Delete the required files and re-run

Retry the Task

Once you have fixed the issue, retry the task. You can retry the task by clicking on the failed task in the DAG graph view and then clicking on the Clear button to clear the task's state.

Once a task has been cleared and has started running, it will be displayed as an open green box. If the task completes successfully, it will be outlined in dark green.

If a cluster of tasks have completed successfully and you wish to rerun a failed task, clear the failed task.

The "Upstream" option selects all tasks upstream of the selected task, while the "Downstream" option selects all tasks downstream of the selected task.

Monitor the Task

After re-running the task, monitor the task to ensure that it completes successfully. You can monitor the task by clicking on the task in the DAG graph view and then clicking on the Graph View tab. The task's status will be displayed in the graph view.

SP Rules

- The reports and algorithms are run only for the active products. So, the products that have sales or inventory in the last 3 years are considered as active in the invent algorithms and reports.
- Products having total sales of “0” for the last 6 months will be out of scope for transfer optimization
- Options (M/Cs) with size-weighted warehouse inventory of greater than or equal to 30 will not be triggered for transfer runs. (This parameter can be changed in UI as well for default runs)
- Invent will maintain a higher percentage for bras (maybe with a different approach from the one explained above) as there are a greater number of sizes per line and majority of the demand is generated from a few sizes.

Rules

1.1 Store Selection

Rules

- Retail stores (owned by LIWA) will be in-scope.
- E-com will be out of scope.
- Stores having no sales for the last 3 weeks will be out-of-scope.
- Stores with sales start date within the last 15 days will be considered as new stores and will be blocked as source stores.

SP

1.2 Pair (Product-Store) Selection for Transfer Runs & Reporting

- Store-option pairs with positive inventory quantity in transit will be blocked as source.
- Freeze period for recently transferred products will be 21 days. This means that the transfer system will allow 21 days for the product transferred to the destination making sure that there will be at least 21 days in between two transfer movements for a specific product.
- Pairs that have their first inventory movements within the last 21 days will be blocked as source.

2.1 Broken Assortment (Size Distribution) Logic:

- Weights different sizes with respect to their sales performances in the last 1 year (underperforming sizes are less important)
- Makes sure that sizes that make up X% of the sales are present at store to minimize broken size ranges

2.2 Broken Assortment (Size Distribution) Calculation Steps:

- Calculate net units sold at model/color/size level on country level for the last 12 months.
- Calculate equivalent sales percentage for S/C/size on country level using these net units sold in the last 12 months.
- Try to satisfy the size threshold parameter in UI given by the user to complete the size distributions at destination.

Size distribution ratio will be set to 70% in the default runs

The replenishment quantity should ideally align with or slightly exceed the forecast to meet client needs while avoiding overstock or lost sales. Here are some checkpoints to ensure the accuracy of the replenishment;

> Note: Remember that factors like limited warehouse inventory, casepack size, presentation stock, min target, max target, or target modifiers such as min dos, outl, additional lead time etc. also be considered in determining the final replenishment solution.

Compare the average sales over a defined period (e.g., the last 14 days) to the cover period forecast. If the sales are trending upward (seasonality etc.), the forecast should reflect this increase. You should also consider outliers, promo sales, etc. But basically, you can implement a rule that flags significant deviations. (e.g., forecast > 150% of sales or forecast < 50% of sales)

Understanding the noob daily process during a handover is crucial because this ensures that the transition is smooth and secure, and maintains the details in forecast operations. Here is a [3.6 Noob ETL- Noob daily] from an existing client.

# Noob Daily Processes

alculation:

Main purpose of the task to calculate an average price of products for a specific period. Then, these average prices will be used in discount calculation. To see default parameters check relevant [noob config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/rocks-noob/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml) section and to see code script [noob asp](https://github.com/inventanalytics/rocks-noob/blob/main/rocks/noob/promotion/asp_calculation.py). Also, as mentioned above, DataBricks parameters section gives information about whether an extension is applied to task. For each task, parameters can be adjusted by [project config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-ebebek2/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml). The table below is a table resulting from the ASP calculation. It is calculated on a per product basis each day. A 15% change in ASP values results in the calculation of a new “group_asp”. Base_price is the max(group_asp) of the last 3 days

results in the calculation of a new “group_asp”. Base_price is the max(group_asp) of the last 3 days. “base_price” and “group_asp” do not change unless there is a 15% change in ASP.

- discount_calculation:

After gathering the average price of products(ASP), group_asp and base_price, this task used to decide if there is a promotion in a specific day. Then, a ratio is calculated to decide how much price is deviate from average price.

Above picture represents;

- at which level (groupby_cols: product_id) daily price will be compared
- to decide deviation will be divided into how many parts and what ratio will be borders. (borders)
- labeling those parts(labels)
- deciding which label will be considered as promotion (labels_that_are_promo)

g those parts(labels)
- deciding which label will be considered as promotion (labels_that_are_promo)

Discount Calculation checks whether there is a discount using the “group_asp” and “base_price” in the table below. If (base_price - group_asp)/base_price is within the discount rates specified in the config, it is assumed that there is a promotion on those days. For example, if we look at the days marked in red, (289.76956 - 221.09236)/289.76956 = 0.237, the 25th and 26th days of February are promotion days.

This task will be updated since client will send promotion information.

- simple_lookup_generator_update

Prepares the training data consisting of sales and inventory information for FC in a lookup format.

- outlier_detection:

Main purpose of the task to decide if a sale in a specific day will be considered as outlier or not. To decide, average sales quantity and standard deviation of sales are calculated in given level.

ot. To decide, average sales quantity and standard deviation of sales are calculated in given level.

Data outside the limits is filtered out (there's no replacement like 'replace with average'). Parameters can be checked from the [config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml)

Above figure shows some part of parameters of outlier_detection task.

- groupby_fetatures: at which level calculations will be done.
- stdev_multip: If a sales exceed this value, it will be considered as outlier.
- rule config: to give algorithm different levels and different rules. As an example, rule with 1st priority, use store-product-discount_bin-day_of_week level but if there is not enough information given in the observation threshold it will not be used. Then, it pass through priority2 and so. Observation can be considered number of data points for given level.

- seasonality_resolve:

Main purpose of the seasonality to give an effect to forecast for specific periods on specific levels. This task gathers previously calculated seasonality coefficients and choose the most convenient one. This coefficient may be calculated in different levels as well as with different calculation methods. To choose the final seasonality MAPE method is applied.

In this step the matching of the FC scope for the day with the FC horizon is done using the coefficients from the seasonality module. Caps have been applied to the seasonality coefficients as given in the [config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml).

- seasonality_with_shares:

To unite the day shares and seasonality coefficients. Day share calculation is done once in a month.

- lltd_lookup_generator:

d seasonality coefficients. Day share calculation is done once in a month.

- lltd_lookup_generator:

To decide how many days before the day will be used in forecasting operation. Below picture shows the relevant config section. *max_lookback*parameter is used for this purpose. Also, day shares that mentioned above is used to adjust sales quantities of specific day.

- lltd_forecast:

After creating all above tables, forecasting operations is run in this task to create several forecast results. Result table is written under noob/forecast in warehouse. Result table contains pair information on forecasting details such as number of observation and first observation day.

- Lead Time for RPL: Lead times are uniformly entered across all countries in the system. Cover periods may differ, but these differences are not due to lead times.
- Distribution from UAE: Direct RPL decisions are not made from UAE warehouse to stores in other countries. Each country has its own warehouse, so UAE distributes first to the country’s warehouse and then from there to the stores.
- Safety Stock Calculation: In cases where the forecast is low, safety stock may be calculated higher than the forecast. However, the customer prefers to maintain higher stock in stores compared to the warehouse. Maximum caps are also used to prevent excessively high targets.

in stores compared to the warehouse. Maximum caps are also used to prevent excessively high targets.
- Seasonality Coefficients: A separate notebook has been created to update seasonality coefficients. This notebook is not scheduled and needs to be run manually. The reason is to avoid the risk of disrupting the results if the coefficients are producing expected outcomes. In Noob_daily, the pre-created seasonality coefficients are used. This notebook was created based on guidelines under the quality_team, and details are in the notebook. It will be checked whether the coefficients are date-based. If so, there might be a need to retrain at least once a year. Coefficients are capped at both lower and upper limits, managed through extensions to prevent absurd values due to data scarcity. These caps were set statically after data analysis. The link to the analysis notebook will be shared.

hese caps were set statically after data analysis. The link to the analysis notebook will be shared.

# Noob ETL Processes

Noob-ETL processes start after update-datastore process. It only reads data from operation bucket and main purpose is to create table that will be used in forecasting processes. Below picture represents the Noob ETL Airflow DAG.

Each task may or may not consists of DataBricks jobs. DataBricks flow will appear after clicking the run_noob_etltask and at the end of page *See DataBricks Job Run* button. Below picture represents the Databricks job.

run_noob_etl consists of 10 main steps;

- Product_agg_level_deduplication: Prevents multiple hierarchies belonging to the same option in different sizes.
- Product_agg_level_generation: Generates product hierarchies.
- store_agg_level_generation: Generates store hierarchies.

- Product_agg_level_deduplication

If the sizes under the same option have different hierarchy information, the hierarchy of all sizes is aligned with the most frequently repeated hierarchy information. At this stage, the products table under the master-data folder in the datastore is taken, and after the deduplication process, it is written as the products-noob table. Only deduplicated data is used in Noob modules. Other modules (i.e., Rocket) do not experience any issues related to duplication.

- cl_product_agg_level_generator, cl_store_agg_level_generator:

any issues related to duplication.

- cl_product_agg_level_generator, cl_store_agg_level_generator:

Aggregation levels are used to create more accurate forecast for store-product pairs whose sales performance are inadequate. Each product and store has specific information. Size and color information can be given as examples for a product as well as region information for a store. agg_level tables are used in several calculations such as day shares and seasonality coefficients.

To see the details check the [liwa noob config section](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml).

- create_holiday_table:

Creates a table that specify special days which affected the sales trend previously and expected to affect in the future as well. It specify global special days such as Valentine’s Day as well as the local special days such as Sacrifice Feast.

To navigate the running code under relevant task and see the job details, After clicking the task below screen will appear. Black box in the below picture shows the parameter set for the job.

e task below screen will appear. Black box in the below picture shows the parameter set for the job.

Each task will be detailed in the documentation may run the default version of the code and also may use the default config of the noob. To distinguish them, check the underline path. Basically If it does not starts with extension, then it is in default mode. Repository of  [default holiday table under rock/noob](https://github.com/inventanalytics/rocks-noob/blob/main/rocks/noob/holiday_table/holiday_table.py) is added. Also, check the [Noob config section](https://github.com/inventanalytics/rocks-noob/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml) to figure out parameter of the relevant task.

Output section of the below screen can be used to find input and output table path of the job by simply searching the ‘read' and 'write’ keywords.

to find input and output table path of the job by simply searching the ‘read' and 'write’ keywords.

The holiday information obtained from the customer is read from the config and a holiday table, which Noob will use, is created. (The file is written to invent-liwa-datastore/noob/holidays/)
We transfer the holidays by inserting them into the `create_holiday_table` table in the [config file](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml) . Every year, we need to obtain an updated version of this data from the customer and update it at least once a year. The project team will work on a more systematic solution for this.

- create_ignore_tables:

Creates tables that will be ignored in the forecasting processes. Table can be in several formats such as Day, Day-Store, Day-Product, Day-ProductGroup. Earthquake happened in February 2023 is an example of ignore table element. Since sales trend in those days are not regular, they eliminated from the process. To add or remove ignore day, changes must be done in `create_ignore_tables` of [liwa noob config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml).

If we don't see any definition, it means we are using the default. It is not actively used.

Below picture illustrates the Day-Store format ignore day addition from Ebebek.
Holiday information is obtained from the customer and updated in the noob config to be included in the holiday tables later. It’s important that the holiday data is updated regularly.

- daily_data:

Daily data contains sales and inventory position of store-product pairs for each day and all processes run through this table. Main columns of the table are Date-Store-Product-Sales-Inventory. There are also additional column like sales revenue and Usable columns. Sales revenue shows the total revenue gained from store-product for relevant day. Usable column used for forecasting operations. If a date-store-product relation is labeled as not usable(0), this day’s sales quantity is not used to create forecast. Previously created ignore table affects this column.

Inventory and sales data are received daily. When this table was first created, all historical data was retrieved. Currently, in the daily process, it adds the last day and updates the previous 6 days. If more days need to be updated retrospectively, the update parameter can be adjusted from the config.

- scope_generator:

scope generator decide product-store pairs which algorithm will create a forecast.

Based on the ruleset that works on sales and inventory data, the RPL FC scope is created. There was also a scope creation methodology on the pre-ETL side. Here, a separate scope process is done specifically for Noob.

solution_id column in the table specify the pairs of different products. For replenishment solution_id should be equal 21. For IA it should be 24.

scope generator task can handle multiple parameters. For detailed parameter explanation and code blocks visit the [default script](https://github.com/inventanalytics/rocks-noob/blob/main/rocks/noob/data_prep/scope_generator.py).

- ia_scope_generator:

The step where we create the IA FC scope using the IA pairs sent by the customer.

- reference_product_store_generator:

Not in use, these will be removed.

- markdown_default_scenario:

Not in use as it hasn't been set up yet.

# Noob Chain Level

Used for forecasting IA products whereas Noob Daily feeds into RPL and TRN runs.
Since IA pairs do not have historical sales data, results cannot be produced from Lltd. Therefore, an ML-based forecasting model (Prophet) is used. The model is not trained daily; once trained, the coefficients are used daily for predictions. The training is done on a notebook, while the prediction runs daily on a DAG.

- cl_in_season:

Flags whether a product is currently in season by analyzing its sales data.

- cl_weekly_enrich:

Similar to daily data but aggregated on a weekly basis. For more robust forecasts, both input and output (prediction) data are at a weekly level. This approach facilitates easier predictions for products with no historical sales data.

- cl_weekly_inventory:

Weekly inventory data used to create broken assortment data.

- cl_weekly_broken_assortment:

Calculates weekly brokenness ratios.

- cl_weekly_lag_features:

ta.

- cl_weekly_broken_assortment:

Calculates weekly brokenness ratios.

- cl_weekly_lag_features:

Computes sales-related statistics (e.g., total sales, average sales) at different hierarchy levels (product or store) and various lag levels. This allows predictions to be made based on statistics that match the hierarchy of the new product. cl_weekly_lag_features identifies which features are used in the parameter given in the [config](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-liwa/blob/main/rocks_extension/noob/config.yml).

- cl_weekly_sales_frequency:

Calculates sales frequency at different hierarchy levels for store and product.

- cl_weekly_seasonality_multiplier_features:

Previously, coefficients were calculated at the product-store level on a daily basis. These coefficients are now aggregated to hierarchy and weekly levels for use in CL.

- cl_weekly_forecast_data_prep:

Creates training and test data using the above four tasks.

in CL.

- cl_weekly_forecast_data_prep:

Creates training and test data using the above four tasks.

- cl_weekly_long_term_forecast_predict:

The stage where predictions are made. Results are at the option-country-week level and need to be broken down to a lower level using the breakdown task:

Option → Size

Country → Store

Week → Day

Additional Notes

- The practice of starting the week on Friday has not been adapted here, but it would not cause a significant change if implemented.
- On Weekly_kpi_report the week starts from Friday.
- Changes were made to the lost sales side as well to start the week from Friday.
- Replenishment Decisions Report will be revised to start the week on Friday.
- Day_effect is not currently used in forecasts. Each day is assigned a 1/7 weight, preparing the structure in case day_effect is needed in the future.

In the Noob chain level task, forecasts created at the option-country-week level are reduced to the size-store-day level as follows:

Option → Size

Country → Store

Week → Day

- size_share:

The ratio of each size’s sales at the PG4 level is calculated.

- store_share:

The ratio of each store’s sales at the country level is calculated.

- breakdown_forecast:

The forecast is broken down to a lower level.

- vectorize:

Results are vectorized for ad-hoc allocation.

Additional Notes

Store or product classification is not available. This classification is not directly provided to the ML model.

- Product_agg_level_2: Brand + PG1 Description + PG2 Description

- Operations: Active in 7 countries: UAE, Bahrain, Kuwait, Qatar, Oman, Egypt, and KSA, with over 45 stores and 2 warehouses.
- Sales Composition: Approximately 22K out of 300K SKUs contribute to 80% of monthly sales.
- Replenishment Strategy:For UAE, Oman, Bahrain, Kuwait, Qatar, and KSA stores, all replenishments are handled from the warehouse (WH) in the UAE.For Egypt stores, replenishments come from the Egypt WH. However, manual allocation is conducted on a weekly basis from the UAE WH to both Egypt stores and its WH.
- Product Categorization: Products are classified in the following order:Business UnitDepartmentProduct Range
- Seasonal Products:Examples include SP21 (Spring), SU21 (Summer), AU21 (Autumn), and WN21 (Winter).Key categories include:LinenSwimwearThermalsWinterwearChristmas

r), AU21 (Autumn), and WN21 (Winter).Key categories include:LinenSwimwearThermalsWinterwearChristmas
- Product Lifecycle: Seasonal products have a lifecycle of 5-7 months, during which we aim to maximize sell-through by allocating stock to the right stores. Products then move to markdowns at the end of the season.
- Promotion Periods:Promotions can last from 1 to 4 weeks:1 week: Trade reaction4 weeks: Planned promotions

1. Best Selling Products of 2023Thermals led in both quantity and revenue, with significant sales primarily during the winter season. This indicates strong seasonal demand for thermal products.
2. BU Performances of 2023Lingerie was the top performer among Business Units (BU) in terms of both quantity sold and revenue. Its sales closely followed seasonal trends, suggesting that lingerie products align well with customer demand patterns.
3. Best Selling StoresThe top five stores contributed to 30% of the total revenue, indicating that a small number of high-performing locations are responsible for a significant portion of sales.
4. Sales Analysis (2022 vs. 2023)There was a slight decline in both sales quantity and revenue when comparing the overall values of 2022 to those of 2023. This trend indicates a slight downturn in sales performance year-over-year.

f 2022 to those of 2023. This trend indicates a slight downturn in sales performance year-over-year.
5. Special Days and Events in 2023Before special events such as Black Friday, Eid al-Fitr, Eid al-Adha, and others, stores increased their stock levels to meet the anticipated demand. Due to border closure issues, stock was sent several weeks in advance for Eid al-Adha to ensure availability.
6. Inventory TrendsA consistent decline in store inventory levels was observed due to lower-than-expected sales. This trend shows efforts to match inventory levels with actual demand to avoid overstocking.
7. Winter Product PerformanceThe sales of thermals, gloves, and other winter products were lower in 2023 than in the previous year due to higher-than-expected temperatures, which reduced the demand for these items.

he previous year due to higher-than-expected temperatures, which reduced the demand for these items.
8. KPI Summary for Regions (AE, KW, QA, SA, BH, OM)Sales performance this year was lower compared to the previous year. The expected sales peak at the end of the year did not occur, primarily due to warmer weather conditions reducing the need for winter apparel.In certain regions like SA and KW, replenishments were suspended as store inventory levels had reached full capacity.There was a slight decrease in Weeks of Supply (WOS) compared to the previous week, indicating tighter inventory management.
9. Sales Return Analysis

- The overall sales return rate was over 40% for 2023, which is relatively high for apparel/fashion items. This indicates a good level of efficiency in transfer decisions, where a significant portion of transferred items sold within eight weeks.

## 2.2 Daily Dag Flow

DAG in Airflow is logged with the previous day's date. *(Marked as yellow)DAG:* [daily](https://afg.airflow.inventanalytics.com/dags/daily/graph)

We should think of adding +3 to all hours in the flow, that is, the flow is triggered at 3 am. Data comes from the customer in 2 batches. The following basic data is sent in the first batch.

Sales | WH Inventory | Inventory | Goods on hold | Goods in transit

If there is missing data, it sends an e-mail. It starts waiting for the data a second time. If the data is complete, it starts copying in. Data is added to the invent-afg/history path.

After the file arrives at 3 am, the run date is calculated and the run id is created. The data after that is associated with that run id. Targets are calculated with the data sent the day before and orders are calculated with the data sent at 3 am.

metadata.title: 2. Data Transfer and Daily Flow Control

content:
e calculated with the data sent the day before and orders are calculated with the data sent at 3 am.

After the first batch data is sent, the pre_etl dag is triggered. In the pre_etl dag, we process the inventory data coming from the customer with our own codes. Raw data can come in a daily or bulk form. We process this incoming data and keep historical data under /operation. Scope does not come directly from the customer, we create it by processing the raw data in our own system. We do this in the pre_etl step.If there is any problem with the data, it raises an error.

metadata.title: 2. Data Transfer and Daily Flow Control

content:
wn system. We do this in the pre_etl step.If there is any problem with the data, it raises an error.

Two separate tasks are created for the triggered sub-dags in the daily flow. One is trigger and the other is wait. When you try to run the Trigger tasks a second time in the same day, it gives an error. For this reason, when you want to run the relevant sub-task again, you need to go to the task itself and clear it with clear downstream from the task you want to run again in that task. The files created in the pre_etl step under invent-afg-datastore/feed are in daily form.

After the pre_etl DAG is completed, the update_datastore_regular DAG is triggered. In this DAG, the data under theinvent-afg-datastore/operation folder in azure is updated. Some data is kept historical, some is kept daily.

metadata.title: 2. Data Transfer and Daily Flow Control

content:
fg-datastore/operation folder in azure is updated. Some data is kept historical, some is kept daily.

Then the rocket_daily DAG is triggered. In the rocket_daily steps, the replenishment decisions to be sent to the client are calculated. These decisions are sent to the client in the send_output step in the daily DAG, along with the previous day's IA decisions. The results should be available by 3:00 PM (6:00 AM in Turkey).

1. Daily Order Control:

- Orders are released every morning at around 5-6.
- The summary of the order results we sent to the customer is in the store and BU breakdown.
- Order is the version where schedule rules are included, therefore it is separated from the detailed result. (We see much higher orders in the detailed_result)
- The orders we sent for newlines are shown separately in columns starting with N, and those we sent within the scope of replenishment are shown separately in columns starting with R.
- In standard times when newlines are not printed much, it is normal to see a bottom total of around 20K.
- If we see a number above this, it would be useful to investigate.

ROP= ReorderPoint (Effective Target)

Option veya size levelda ROP iletilebilir.

- Bu optiondan bu storede şu kadar stok olmasını istiyorum. → size breakdown logic ile size’lara kırılır
- Bu sizeden bu storeda şu kadar stok olmasını istiyorum → direk uygulanır

## Mail

ROP’ler haftaiçi her gün müşteri tarafından maille iletilir. Tüm BU’lar için ortak bir doküman iletilir.

Mailin ekinde aşağıdaki gibi bir csv dosyası bulunur. (Option bazlı ilettikleri data örneği)

tilir.

Mailin ekinde aşağıdaki gibi bir csv dosyası bulunur. (Option bazlı ilettikleri data örneği)

- BU: Product group 1. Aynı dosyada birden fazla BU’ya ait optionlar bulunabilir.
- Option: option_code
- Store: store_code
- New Line Flag: kendi içlerinde ayrıştırma yapabilmek için kullanıyorlar. Mahmut da yazabilirler:D Sadece option levelde iletilir.1: warehouse stoklarını dikkate alarak kır0: son 6da satış performasına göre kır
- Suggested QT: ROP
- Suggested Type: ROP veya order değerlerini alabilir. ROP ise target’a cap koyuyoruz. Order ise order’a cap koyuyoruz. Yani mağazadaki inventory’i al üzerine Suggested QT kadar ekle ve ROP olarak set et.
- Warehouse: warehouse_code. Default 1200.

al üzerine Suggested QT kadar ekle ve ROP olarak set et.

Hardcoded ROP vermek yerine aşağıdaki 3 parametreyi vererek ROP’yi bizim hesaplamamızı isteyebilirler. Örneğin son 4 haftanın satışına bak. Week cover 4 olacak şekilde olması gereken stok seviyesini hesapla. Gerekirse bunu da bir çarpanla düzelt gibi. Eğer bu üç kolonu doldurdularsa Suggested QT’yi boş bırakmaları gerekiyor. Bununla ilgili notebookda bir kontrol var. Bu şekilde satırlar varsa müşteriye maille soruyoruz hangisi geçerli olsun diye.

- Last x Weeks AVG Sales: son kaç haftanın satışına bakacak.
- WC: week cover
- UpliftedRatio: çarpan.
- ROP Update Type: min, max, fix
- Validity Period End Date: hangi tarihe kadar geçerli olsun
- Is Manual PO or Not: boolean. 1: manual PO. tek seferlik sonuçları maille iletiyoruz.0: validity period end date’e kadar geçerli

3. Eğer bu ürünler daha önceden başka bir BU ile geliyorduysa zaten satış ve stok kayıtları olduğundan scope’a girebilir ama yepyeni ürünlerse ve müşteri bunlar için target paylaştıysa bu targetların tanımlanması ve bu pairlerin scope_addition.csv dosyasına eklenmesi gerekir.

5. Reporting tasklarınında BU filtreleniyor olabilir, bunlara bakılıp ekleme yapılmalı.
6. Nerelere ekleme yapılacağını belirlemenin en temiz yolu alfuttaim reposunda JAEGER veya KIDSWEAR gibi bir BU ismini aratmak ve kontrol etmektir. Son adımda bu yapılırsa yeni BU için sonuç çıktığına ve raporlarda yer aldığına emin olunabilir.

Initial Design:

- range: şurada range de select edilmeli, sonrasında dept ve pg1 kullanılan her yerde kontrol edilmeli, join ve group by için
- size_count: şuraya cap values joinleyip (joinlerken bu-dept-range-store-flag-size_count üzerinden bir join, range olmadan bir join) size count eşleşenleri al, eşleşmeyenleri (null gelen) no_constraint yap demek lazım.
- cap values join: şurada cap values joinlenirken artık range de eklenmeli ama range eşleşmeyenler için dept eşleyerek devam ediyor olmamız lazım. bunun için de 1. önce range ile eşleyelim, eşlenmeyenlere no_range girelim, tekrar eşleyelim. eksik kalan oluyor mu vs count, duplicate vs checkleri yapalım

- Testler tamamlanıp canlıya alındı. invent-afg-datastore/internal-data/ia_target_cap_values.csv dosyası yeni formata çevrildi.
- Müşteri tarafından range ve farklı size_count seviyelerinde iletilen cap valuelar eşleşme sağlanan durumlarda uygulanacak, eşleşme olmayanlarda no_range ve no_size_constraint işaretli (eski versiyondaki gibi) capler uygulanacak.
- Şu an range ve farklı size kırılımları için cap valueları lingerie ve womenswear gönderdiği için bu değişiklik onlar için geçerli. Diğer BUlar da gönderirse dosyaya uygun şekilde ekleme yapılmalı.
- Range seviyesinde cap iletilmeyenler için department seviyesinde cap value uygulanması için no_range yazanlar silinmemeli, müşteriye gerekli bilgilendirme yapılarak dosya güncel tutulmalı.

çin no_range yazanlar silinmemeli, müşteriye gerekli bilgilendirme yapılarak dosya güncel tutulmalı.

WOS:

- Using WOS to allocate warehouse stock is not an ideal approach. Instead, in push-driven cases, it is more accurate to run the allocation by checking the Order Box option.
- The target is calculated as: Target = CP Forecast + Safety Stock. However, when WOS is selected, the safety stock is treated as zero, so the formula becomes Target = CP Forecast. After this step, the target might slightly change due to Target Modifiers.

PUSH DRIVEN:Push Allocation For All Selections:

The units entered in this field are related to the total recommended quantity that will result from the relevant allocation run.

If the Order checkbox shown above is ticked, the total number of orders generated across all products in the run will be 27.
If it is not ticked, the total of store stock + in-transit stock + order quantity across all products will sum up to 27 instead.

Edit In Detail:

If we want to assign quantities at different aggregation levels (such as option-store, SKU-store, option only, etc.) instead of setting a total order quantity for the entire run, we use this section. Here, you can define the quantity at your desired level.

For example, in the case below, 60 units have been entered for each relevant option-store pair.
If the Order checkbox is ticked, the system will try to generate 60 orders per option-store.
If it is not ticked, the system will try to ensure that the store stock + incoming stock + order quantity equals 60 per option-store.

Note: If we want to see what appears on the *Edit in Detail* screen when the client runs the process, and how the client has made the definitions, we can refer to the following path:

t runs the process, and how the client has made the definitions, we can refer to the following path:

*allocation/ad-hoc/runs/<run_id>/input/*Note: If we want to see how this definition has been reflected in the system, we can go to the following path:

*allocation/ad-hoc/allocation_target_by_pair/run_id =<runid>*Note: In desired order calculations, benefit and cost metrics are taken into account. Therefore, in push-driven cases, the quantities entered in the UI do not always mean that the system will generate exactly that amount of orders at the specified level.

The system attempts to align the order quantity with the entered level, but if there is no additional benefit (based on constraints or benefit & cost analysis) from sending more orders, it does not force the order quantity to match the user-defined input.

sis) from sending more orders, it does not force the order quantity to match the user-defined input.

For example, in runId = 47, 60 units were entered per option-store in the *Edit in Detail* screen, and the Order checkbox was selected. However, for store 1201, only 55 units of the relevant option were sent, even though there was still warehouse stock available for SKU 60624074006 under that option.

When we examine the total benefits, we see that the algorithm did not attempt to send the remaining 5 units from this SKU to that store, as the maximum benefit it could achieve for this sku-store pair was already reached at 26 units. In other words, beyond 26 units, the algorithm expects no additional profit, based on probability of sales.

This probability of sales is linked to the forecast, and most likely, the fixed inventory quantity of 60 was relatively high compared to the forecast.
